+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LVRcAvdYQUtjJCHmwCu37y","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All 60 tests pass. Now I have a complete picture. Let me provide the thorough code review.\n\n---\n\n## Code Review: 8 SSG Plugins\n\nAll 60 tests across 8 test suites pass. Below are my findings categorized by priority.\n\n---\n\n### HIGH PRIORITY FINDINGS\n\n#### HIGH-1: `markdown-ext.ts` -- Admonition regex fails unless content has a trailing newline\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/markdown-ext.ts`, line 31\n\n```typescript\ncontent = content.replace(/^:::(note|warning|tip)\\n([\\s\\S]*?)^:::/gm, (_match, type: string, body: string) => {\n  return `<div class=\"admonition admonition-${type}\">\\n${body.trim()}\\n</div>`;\n});\n```\n\nThe regex uses `^:::` with the multiline flag (`m`) to anchor the closing `:::` to the start of a line. However, `^` in multiline mode matches after a `\\n` character. If the closing `:::` is on the very last line of the string with no trailing newline, `^:::` at the end **will** match (because `^` in multiline mode also matches the start of the string). But the real danger is in the test inputs. Consider the test on line 59 of the test file:\n\n```typescript\nconst file = makeFile({ content: ':::note\\nThis is a note.\\n:::' });\n```\n\nThis works because the closing `:::` is preceded by `\\n`, allowing `^` to match. However, if admonitions are embedded mid-document followed by more content without an explicit newline before `:::`, the greedy `[\\s\\S]*?` could cause unexpected behavior. More critically, **the regex only matches `\\d+` for footnote IDs** (see HIGH-2 below), and the admonition capture group `([\\s\\S]*?)` combined with `^:::` is fragile when multiple admonitions appear in the same document since `[\\s\\S]*?` can cross admonition boundaries if formatting is slightly off.\n\nThe tests pass with the current inputs, but this is a latent fragility. The regex is one malformed input away from producing garbage HTML.\n\n---\n\n#### HIGH-2: `markdown-ext.ts` -- Footnotes only support numeric IDs, but no validation or error message\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/markdown-ext.ts`, lines 20 and 26\n\n```typescript\n// Definition: only matches digits\ncontent = content.replace(/^\\[\\^(\\d+)\\]:\\s*(.+)$/gm, (_match, id: string, text: string) => {\n  footnotes.set(id, text);\n  return '';\n});\n\n// Reference: also only matches digits\ncontent = content.replace(/\\[\\^(\\d+)\\]/g, (_match, id: string) => {\n  return `<sup><a href=\"#fn-${id}\">${id}</a></sup>`;\n});\n```\n\nBoth regexes use `\\d+`, meaning text-based footnote IDs like `[^note]` are silently ignored. This is consistent between definition and reference patterns, and the tests only test numeric IDs, so everything passes. However, standard footnote syntax (e.g., in CommonMark extensions, Pandoc, PHP Markdown Extra) supports alphanumeric footnote labels like `[^myref]`. If any upstream content uses non-numeric footnote IDs, they will be silently dropped with no warning -- the definitions will remain in the output as literal text and the references will not be linked.\n\n**Recommendation:** Either broaden the regex to `[\\w-]+` to support alphanumeric footnote IDs, or document the numeric-only restriction prominently and add a warning/error for non-numeric IDs.\n\n---\n\n#### HIGH-3: `markdown-ext.ts` -- Orphaned footnote references produce broken links\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/markdown-ext.ts`, lines 26-28\n\nIf content references `[^3]` but no definition `[^3]: ...` exists, the code will still emit `<sup><a href=\"#fn-3\">3</a></sup>` linking to an anchor `#fn-3` that does not exist in the footnotes section (or the footnotes section may not be rendered at all if no definitions matched). The tests do not cover this edge case. This produces broken anchor links in the output HTML.\n\n**Recommendation:** After processing, check for references that have no corresponding definition and either strip them or emit a build-time warning.\n\n---\n\n#### HIGH-4: `rss-feed.ts` -- No XML escaping of title, link, or content values\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/rss-feed.ts`, lines 26-31\n\n```typescript\nreturn `    <item>\n      <title>${file.title}</title>\n      <link>${config.baseUrl}/${file.slug}.html</link>\n${pubDate}      <description><![CDATA[${file.content}]]></description>\n${categories}\n    </item>`;\n```\n\nAnd lines 37-39:\n\n```typescript\n    <title>${config.title}</title>\n    <link>${config.baseUrl}</link>\n    <description>${config.title} RSS Feed</description>\n```\n\nIf `file.title` contains characters like `&`, `<`, or `>`, the generated XML will be malformed. For example, a title like `\"Tom & Jerry\"` would produce `<title>Tom & Jerry</title>` which is invalid XML. The `<description>` field uses `CDATA` which protects the content, but `<title>`, `<link>`, `<category>`, and the channel-level `<description>` are all unescaped.\n\nThe tests pass because no test input contains XML-special characters. This is a correctness bug that will produce invalid RSS for real-world content.\n\n**Recommendation:** Add an `escapeXml()` utility that replaces `&`, `<`, `>`, `\"`, and `'` with their XML entities, and apply it to all interpolated values outside CDATA sections.\n\n---\n\n#### HIGH-5: `rss-feed.ts` -- Trailing empty line in category output creates malformed XML\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/rss-feed.ts`, lines 29-30\n\n```typescript\n      <description><![CDATA[${file.content}]]></description>\n${categories}\n    </item>`;\n```\n\nWhen `categories` is non-empty, the template produces output like:\n\n```xml\n      <description><![CDATA[content]]></description>\n      <category>javascript</category>\n\n    </item>\n```\n\nNote the blank line between the last `<category>` and `</item>`. When `categories` is an empty string (no tags), the output produces:\n\n```xml\n      <description><![CDATA[content]]></description>\n\n    </item>\n```\n\nThis extra blank line appears because `${categories}\\n` always adds a newline. While technically valid XML (whitespace is allowed), it is messy and could trip up strict XML parsers or diff-based tests. The tests currently pass because they use `toContain` rather than exact matching.\n\n---\n\n#### HIGH-6: `sitemap.ts` -- Sitemap does not exclude `search-index.json` or `feed.xml` itself\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/sitemap.ts`, lines 13-16\n\n```typescript\nfor (const key of output.keys()) {\n  if (key === 'sitemap.xml') continue;\n  urls.push(`${config.baseUrl}/${key}`);\n}\n```\n\nThe sitemap correctly excludes itself (`sitemap.xml`) but includes `feed.xml` and `search-index.json` as URLs. The test on line 61-68 explicitly verifies that `feed.xml` IS included. While technically not wrong (some sites do include their feed in the sitemap), including `search-index.json` in a sitemap is semantically incorrect -- it is a machine-readable JSON file, not a page intended for search engine crawling.\n\n**Assessment:** The code matches the tests. The test for `feed.xml` inclusion was intentional. However, `search-index.json` being included in the sitemap is questionable. If a test for this is added later, it would pass with the current implementation, but it likely should be filtered out.\n\n---\n\n### MEDIUM PRIORITY FINDINGS\n\n#### MEDIUM-1: `markdown-ext.ts` -- `marked.parse()` called with `{ async: false }` but return value cast as string\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/markdown-ext.ts`, line 36\n\n```typescript\ncontent = marked.parse(content, { async: false }) as string;\n```\n\nThe `as string` cast is necessary because `marked.parse` returns `string | Promise<string>`. When `async: false` is passed, it is synchronous and returns `string`. The cast is correct but brittle -- if the `marked` library changes its API or if someone removes `{ async: false }`, this will silently return a Promise object cast as a string, producing `[object Promise]` in the output. The test calls the hook with `await` (line 38 of test), so if the function ever becomes async, the tests would still work, but the cast would hide the issue.\n\n**Recommendation:** Consider using `marked.parseInline` where appropriate, or add a runtime type check.\n\n---\n\n#### MEDIUM-2: `asset-pipeline.ts` -- Regex only matches `./` relative paths, misses `../` and bare relative paths\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/asset-pipeline.ts`, line 17\n\n```typescript\nconst content = file.content.replace(\n  /(src|href)=\"\\.\\/([^\"]+)\"/g,\n  ...\n);\n```\n\nThe regex only rewrites paths starting with `./`. Paths like `src=\"../images/photo.png\"` or `src=\"images/photo.png\"` (no `./` prefix) will not be rewritten. The tests only test `./` paths and absolute URLs, so they all pass.\n\nThis is a significant limitation for real-world usage. Content authored in subdirectories commonly uses `../` paths, and many authoring tools produce bare relative paths without the `./` prefix.\n\n**Recommendation:** Expand the regex to handle `../` paths and bare relative paths, or document that only `./`-prefixed paths are supported.\n\n---\n\n#### MEDIUM-3: `asset-pipeline.ts` -- Only matches `src` and `href` attributes\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/asset-pipeline.ts`, line 17\n\nThe regex `/(src|href)=\"\\.\\/([^\"]+)\"/g` only matches `src` and `href`. Other asset-referencing attributes like `srcset`, `poster` (for video), or `data-src` (for lazy loading) are not handled. This is consistent with the tests but is a limitation worth noting.\n\n---\n\n#### MEDIUM-4: `search-index.ts` -- `stripHtml` function is naive and can produce mangled text\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/search-index.ts`, lines 3-5\n\n```typescript\nfunction stripHtml(html: string): string {\n  return html.replace(/<[^>]+>/g, '').trim();\n}\n```\n\nThis regex-based HTML stripping has known limitations:\n- Content like `5 < 10 and 20 > 15` would be mangled (the `< 10 and 20 >` portion would be stripped as if it were a tag).\n- HTML entities like `&amp;`, `&lt;`, `&gt;` are not decoded, so indexed content may contain literal `&amp;` strings.\n- Self-closing tags with attributes containing `>` could break the regex.\n\nThe tests pass because the test content is well-formed HTML without edge cases. For a search index, mangled content degrades search quality.\n\n---\n\n#### MEDIUM-5: `taxonomy.ts` -- Tag page HTML generation uses non-escaped file titles\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/taxonomy.ts`, line 32\n\n```typescript\nconst items = files.map(f => `<li><a href=\"/${f.slug}.html\">${f.title}</a></li>`).join('\\n');\n```\n\nIf `f.title` contains HTML special characters (e.g., `\"How to use <template> tags\"`), the output HTML will be malformed. The title would be interpreted as HTML rather than displayed as text.\n\n**Recommendation:** Add HTML escaping for interpolated values in generated HTML.\n\n---\n\n#### MEDIUM-6: `taxonomy.ts` -- Tag page URL format inconsistent with RSS feed URL format\n\nThe taxonomy plugin generates links as `/${f.slug}.html` (line 32):\n```typescript\n`<li><a href=\"/${f.slug}.html\">${f.title}</a></li>`\n```\n\nThe RSS feed plugin generates links as `${config.baseUrl}/${file.slug}.html` (line 28 of `rss-feed.ts`):\n```typescript\n<link>${config.baseUrl}/${file.slug}.html</link>\n```\n\nThe taxonomy plugin uses root-relative URLs (no baseUrl), while the RSS feed uses absolute URLs. This inconsistency means tag pages will produce broken links if the site is hosted under a subpath (e.g., `https://example.com/blog/`).\n\n---\n\n#### MEDIUM-7: `dev-server.ts` -- `searchIndexPath` remains empty string when `search-index.json` is absent\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/dev-server.ts`, lines 23, 30-32\n\n```typescript\nlet searchIndexPath = '';\n...\nif (key === 'search-index.json') {\n  searchIndexPath = '/search-index.json';\n}\n```\n\nWhen the `search-index` plugin has not run (or produced no output), `searchIndexPath` defaults to `''`. Downstream consumers of the `DevServerConfig` would need to check for an empty string rather than `null` or `undefined`. The test on line 89-94 of the test file covers this case (checking `assetPaths` is empty), but does not verify `searchIndexPath` when the search index is absent. This is a minor data modeling issue -- using `null` or `undefined` would be semantically clearer.\n\n---\n\n#### MEDIUM-8: `markdown-ext.ts` -- Empty content check inconsistency\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/markdown-ext.ts`, lines 13-15\n\n```typescript\nif (!content) {\n  return { ...file, content: '' };\n}\n```\n\nThe check `!content` is truthy for both empty string `\"\"` and `undefined`/`null`. However, `ContentFile.content` is typed as `string` (not optional), so it should never be `undefined` or `null`. The early return for empty string bypasses `marked.parse`, which would return `\"\"` for `\"\"` input anyway. This is harmless but the guard is slightly misleading -- it appears to handle null safety for a non-nullable field.\n\n---\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| # | Plugin | Priority | Issue |\n|---|--------|----------|-------|\n| HIGH-1 | markdown-ext | HIGH | Admonition regex fragile with edge-case formatting |\n| HIGH-2 | markdown-ext | HIGH | Footnotes silently ignore non-numeric IDs |\n| HIGH-3 | markdown-ext | HIGH | Orphaned footnote references produce broken anchor links |\n| HIGH-4 | rss-feed | HIGH | No XML escaping for titles, links, or categories |\n| HIGH-5 | rss-feed | HIGH | Trailing blank line in item output from category template |\n| HIGH-6 | sitemap | HIGH | Includes `search-index.json` in sitemap (non-page resource) |\n| MEDIUM-1 | markdown-ext | MEDIUM | Brittle `as string` cast on `marked.parse()` return |\n| MEDIUM-2 | asset-pipeline | MEDIUM | Only handles `./` relative paths, misses `../` and bare relative |\n| MEDIUM-3 | asset-pipeline | MEDIUM | Only matches `src`/`href` attributes, misses `srcset`/`poster`/etc. |\n| MEDIUM-4 | search-index | MEDIUM | Naive `stripHtml` can mangle text with `<`/`>` in content |\n| MEDIUM-5 | taxonomy | MEDIUM | File titles not HTML-escaped in generated tag pages |\n| MEDIUM-6 | taxonomy | MEDIUM | Root-relative URLs in tag pages vs absolute URLs in RSS feed |\n| MEDIUM-7 | dev-server | MEDIUM | `searchIndexPath` uses empty string instead of null when absent |\n| MEDIUM-8 | markdown-ext | MEDIUM | Unnecessary null guard for non-nullable `content` field |\n\n### What was done well\n\n- All 60 tests pass cleanly and the test coverage is solid for the happy path.\n- Plugin architecture is clean: each plugin is a pure factory function returning a `Plugin` interface with clearly separated hook phases (`beforeBuild`, `transformContent`, `afterBuild`).\n- Cross-plugin data sharing via `ctx.data` is well-designed and consistently used (e.g., `asset-manifest`, `taxonomy-tags`, `dev-server-config`).\n- Dependencies are correctly declared in each plugin's `dependencies` array, matching actual data flow (e.g., `rss-feed` depends on `markdown-ext` and `taxonomy`; `dev-server` depends on `asset-pipeline` and `search-index`).\n- Immutability is respected: `transformContent` hooks return new objects via spread (`{ ...file, content }`) rather than mutating the input.\n- The `sitemap` plugin correctly self-excludes to avoid infinite recursion.\n- Test helpers (`makeCtx`, `makeFile`) are well-factored and consistent across all 8 test files.\n\n### Key Recommendations\n\n1. **Highest impact fix:** Add an `escapeXml()` utility and apply it in `rss-feed.ts` for all interpolated values outside CDATA. This is the most likely bug to manifest with real-world content (titles containing `&`).\n\n2. **Second highest impact:** Add an `escapeHtml()` utility and apply it in `taxonomy.ts` tag page generation. Same class of bug as the XML escaping issue.\n\n3. **Third:** Expand footnote ID support in `markdown-ext.ts` from `\\d+` to `[\\w-]+` to match common Markdown footnote conventions, or add explicit documentation noting the numeric-only limitation.\n\n4. **Fourth:** Improve `stripHtml()` in `search-index.ts` to also decode HTML entities after stripping tags, using a simple entity map for `&amp;`, `&lt;`, `&gt;`, `&quot;`, `&#39;`."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a1d2dde (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 34557\ntool_uses: 21\nduration_ms: 112197</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1812e0c7-6cf2-41d2-afeb-9d6c0a577574","uuid":"2f9a6848-2bea-4c50-a98f-780f8324b142","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review the implementation of 8 SSG plugins against the test expectations. The plugins are in /workspace/src/plugins/. The test files are in /workspace/tests/plugins/. Review each plugin for:\n1. Correctness against test expectations\n2. Edge cases\n3. Code quality\n4. Any issues that could cause failures\n\nRead all 8 plugin files and their corresponding test files. Report any HIGH or MEDIUM priority findings.","agentId":"a1d2dde","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All 60 tests pass. Now I have a complete picture. Let me provide the thorough code review.\n\n---\n\n## Code Review: 8 SSG Plugins\n\nAll 60 tests across 8 test suites pass. Below are my findings categorized by priority.\n\n---\n\n### HIGH PRIORITY FINDINGS\n\n#### HIGH-1: `markdown-ext.ts` -- Admonition regex fails unless content has a trailing newline\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/markdown-ext.ts`, line 31\n\n```typescript\ncontent = content.replace(/^:::(note|warning|tip)\\n([\\s\\S]*?)^:::/gm, (_match, type: string, body: string) => {\n  return `<div class=\"admonition admonition-${type}\">\\n${body.trim()}\\n</div>`;\n});\n```\n\nThe regex uses `^:::` with the multiline flag (`m`) to anchor the closing `:::` to the start of a line. However, `^` in multiline mode matches after a `\\n` character. If the closing `:::` is on the very last line of the string with no trailing newline, `^:::` at the end **will** match (because `^` in multiline mode also matches the start of the string). But the real danger is in the test inputs. Consider the test on line 59 of the test file:\n\n```typescript\nconst file = makeFile({ content: ':::note\\nThis is a note.\\n:::' });\n```\n\nThis works because the closing `:::` is preceded by `\\n`, allowing `^` to match. However, if admonitions are embedded mid-document followed by more content without an explicit newline before `:::`, the greedy `[\\s\\S]*?` could cause unexpected behavior. More critically, **the regex only matches `\\d+` for footnote IDs** (see HIGH-2 below), and the admonition capture group `([\\s\\S]*?)` combined with `^:::` is fragile when multiple admonitions appear in the same document since `[\\s\\S]*?` can cross admonition boundaries if formatting is slightly off.\n\nThe tests pass with the current inputs, but this is a latent fragility. The regex is one malformed input away from producing garbage HTML.\n\n---\n\n#### HIGH-2: `markdown-ext.ts` -- Footnotes only support numeric IDs, but no validation or error message\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/markdown-ext.ts`, lines 20 and 26\n\n```typescript\n// Definition: only matches digits\ncontent = content.replace(/^\\[\\^(\\d+)\\]:\\s*(.+)$/gm, (_match, id: string, text: string) => {\n  footnotes.set(id, text);\n  return '';\n});\n\n// Reference: also only matches digits\ncontent = content.replace(/\\[\\^(\\d+)\\]/g, (_match, id: string) => {\n  return `<sup><a href=\"#fn-${id}\">${id}</a></sup>`;\n});\n```\n\nBoth regexes use `\\d+`, meaning text-based footnote IDs like `[^note]` are silently ignored. This is consistent between definition and reference patterns, and the tests only test numeric IDs, so everything passes. However, standard footnote syntax (e.g., in CommonMark extensions, Pandoc, PHP Markdown Extra) supports alphanumeric footnote labels like `[^myref]`. If any upstream content uses non-numeric footnote IDs, they will be silently dropped with no warning -- the definitions will remain in the output as literal text and the references will not be linked.\n\n**Recommendation:** Either broaden the regex to `[\\w-]+` to support alphanumeric footnote IDs, or document the numeric-only restriction prominently and add a warning/error for non-numeric IDs.\n\n---\n\n#### HIGH-3: `markdown-ext.ts` -- Orphaned footnote references produce broken links\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/markdown-ext.ts`, lines 26-28\n\nIf content references `[^3]` but no definition `[^3]: ...` exists, the code will still emit `<sup><a href=\"#fn-3\">3</a></sup>` linking to an anchor `#fn-3` that does not exist in the footnotes section (or the footnotes section may not be rendered at all if no definitions matched). The tests do not cover this edge case. This produces broken anchor links in the output HTML.\n\n**Recommendation:** After processing, check for references that have no corresponding definition and either strip them or emit a build-time warning.\n\n---\n\n#### HIGH-4: `rss-feed.ts` -- No XML escaping of title, link, or content values\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/rss-feed.ts`, lines 26-31\n\n```typescript\nreturn `    <item>\n      <title>${file.title}</title>\n      <link>${config.baseUrl}/${file.slug}.html</link>\n${pubDate}      <description><![CDATA[${file.content}]]></description>\n${categories}\n    </item>`;\n```\n\nAnd lines 37-39:\n\n```typescript\n    <title>${config.title}</title>\n    <link>${config.baseUrl}</link>\n    <description>${config.title} RSS Feed</description>\n```\n\nIf `file.title` contains characters like `&`, `<`, or `>`, the generated XML will be malformed. For example, a title like `\"Tom & Jerry\"` would produce `<title>Tom & Jerry</title>` which is invalid XML. The `<description>` field uses `CDATA` which protects the content, but `<title>`, `<link>`, `<category>`, and the channel-level `<description>` are all unescaped.\n\nThe tests pass because no test input contains XML-special characters. This is a correctness bug that will produce invalid RSS for real-world content.\n\n**Recommendation:** Add an `escapeXml()` utility that replaces `&`, `<`, `>`, `\"`, and `'` with their XML entities, and apply it to all interpolated values outside CDATA sections.\n\n---\n\n#### HIGH-5: `rss-feed.ts` -- Trailing empty line in category output creates malformed XML\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/rss-feed.ts`, lines 29-30\n\n```typescript\n      <description><![CDATA[${file.content}]]></description>\n${categories}\n    </item>`;\n```\n\nWhen `categories` is non-empty, the template produces output like:\n\n```xml\n      <description><![CDATA[content]]></description>\n      <category>javascript</category>\n\n    </item>\n```\n\nNote the blank line between the last `<category>` and `</item>`. When `categories` is an empty string (no tags), the output produces:\n\n```xml\n      <description><![CDATA[content]]></description>\n\n    </item>\n```\n\nThis extra blank line appears because `${categories}\\n` always adds a newline. While technically valid XML (whitespace is allowed), it is messy and could trip up strict XML parsers or diff-based tests. The tests currently pass because they use `toContain` rather than exact matching.\n\n---\n\n#### HIGH-6: `sitemap.ts` -- Sitemap does not exclude `search-index.json` or `feed.xml` itself\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/sitemap.ts`, lines 13-16\n\n```typescript\nfor (const key of output.keys()) {\n  if (key === 'sitemap.xml') continue;\n  urls.push(`${config.baseUrl}/${key}`);\n}\n```\n\nThe sitemap correctly excludes itself (`sitemap.xml`) but includes `feed.xml` and `search-index.json` as URLs. The test on line 61-68 explicitly verifies that `feed.xml` IS included. While technically not wrong (some sites do include their feed in the sitemap), including `search-index.json` in a sitemap is semantically incorrect -- it is a machine-readable JSON file, not a page intended for search engine crawling.\n\n**Assessment:** The code matches the tests. The test for `feed.xml` inclusion was intentional. However, `search-index.json` being included in the sitemap is questionable. If a test for this is added later, it would pass with the current implementation, but it likely should be filtered out.\n\n---\n\n### MEDIUM PRIORITY FINDINGS\n\n#### MEDIUM-1: `markdown-ext.ts` -- `marked.parse()` called with `{ async: false }` but return value cast as string\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/markdown-ext.ts`, line 36\n\n```typescript\ncontent = marked.parse(content, { async: false }) as string;\n```\n\nThe `as string` cast is necessary because `marked.parse` returns `string | Promise<string>`. When `async: false` is passed, it is synchronous and returns `string`. The cast is correct but brittle -- if the `marked` library changes its API or if someone removes `{ async: false }`, this will silently return a Promise object cast as a string, producing `[object Promise]` in the output. The test calls the hook with `await` (line 38 of test), so if the function ever becomes async, the tests would still work, but the cast would hide the issue.\n\n**Recommendation:** Consider using `marked.parseInline` where appropriate, or add a runtime type check.\n\n---\n\n#### MEDIUM-2: `asset-pipeline.ts` -- Regex only matches `./` relative paths, misses `../` and bare relative paths\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/asset-pipeline.ts`, line 17\n\n```typescript\nconst content = file.content.replace(\n  /(src|href)=\"\\.\\/([^\"]+)\"/g,\n  ...\n);\n```\n\nThe regex only rewrites paths starting with `./`. Paths like `src=\"../images/photo.png\"` or `src=\"images/photo.png\"` (no `./` prefix) will not be rewritten. The tests only test `./` paths and absolute URLs, so they all pass.\n\nThis is a significant limitation for real-world usage. Content authored in subdirectories commonly uses `../` paths, and many authoring tools produce bare relative paths without the `./` prefix.\n\n**Recommendation:** Expand the regex to handle `../` paths and bare relative paths, or document that only `./`-prefixed paths are supported.\n\n---\n\n#### MEDIUM-3: `asset-pipeline.ts` -- Only matches `src` and `href` attributes\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/asset-pipeline.ts`, line 17\n\nThe regex `/(src|href)=\"\\.\\/([^\"]+)\"/g` only matches `src` and `href`. Other asset-referencing attributes like `srcset`, `poster` (for video), or `data-src` (for lazy loading) are not handled. This is consistent with the tests but is a limitation worth noting.\n\n---\n\n#### MEDIUM-4: `search-index.ts` -- `stripHtml` function is naive and can produce mangled text\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/search-index.ts`, lines 3-5\n\n```typescript\nfunction stripHtml(html: string): string {\n  return html.replace(/<[^>]+>/g, '').trim();\n}\n```\n\nThis regex-based HTML stripping has known limitations:\n- Content like `5 < 10 and 20 > 15` would be mangled (the `< 10 and 20 >` portion would be stripped as if it were a tag).\n- HTML entities like `&amp;`, `&lt;`, `&gt;` are not decoded, so indexed content may contain literal `&amp;` strings.\n- Self-closing tags with attributes containing `>` could break the regex.\n\nThe tests pass because the test content is well-formed HTML without edge cases. For a search index, mangled content degrades search quality.\n\n---\n\n#### MEDIUM-5: `taxonomy.ts` -- Tag page HTML generation uses non-escaped file titles\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/taxonomy.ts`, line 32\n\n```typescript\nconst items = files.map(f => `<li><a href=\"/${f.slug}.html\">${f.title}</a></li>`).join('\\n');\n```\n\nIf `f.title` contains HTML special characters (e.g., `\"How to use <template> tags\"`), the output HTML will be malformed. The title would be interpreted as HTML rather than displayed as text.\n\n**Recommendation:** Add HTML escaping for interpolated values in generated HTML.\n\n---\n\n#### MEDIUM-6: `taxonomy.ts` -- Tag page URL format inconsistent with RSS feed URL format\n\nThe taxonomy plugin generates links as `/${f.slug}.html` (line 32):\n```typescript\n`<li><a href=\"/${f.slug}.html\">${f.title}</a></li>`\n```\n\nThe RSS feed plugin generates links as `${config.baseUrl}/${file.slug}.html` (line 28 of `rss-feed.ts`):\n```typescript\n<link>${config.baseUrl}/${file.slug}.html</link>\n```\n\nThe taxonomy plugin uses root-relative URLs (no baseUrl), while the RSS feed uses absolute URLs. This inconsistency means tag pages will produce broken links if the site is hosted under a subpath (e.g., `https://example.com/blog/`).\n\n---\n\n#### MEDIUM-7: `dev-server.ts` -- `searchIndexPath` remains empty string when `search-index.json` is absent\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/dev-server.ts`, lines 23, 30-32\n\n```typescript\nlet searchIndexPath = '';\n...\nif (key === 'search-index.json') {\n  searchIndexPath = '/search-index.json';\n}\n```\n\nWhen the `search-index` plugin has not run (or produced no output), `searchIndexPath` defaults to `''`. Downstream consumers of the `DevServerConfig` would need to check for an empty string rather than `null` or `undefined`. The test on line 89-94 of the test file covers this case (checking `assetPaths` is empty), but does not verify `searchIndexPath` when the search index is absent. This is a minor data modeling issue -- using `null` or `undefined` would be semantically clearer.\n\n---\n\n#### MEDIUM-8: `markdown-ext.ts` -- Empty content check inconsistency\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/markdown-ext.ts`, lines 13-15\n\n```typescript\nif (!content) {\n  return { ...file, content: '' };\n}\n```\n\nThe check `!content` is truthy for both empty string `\"\"` and `undefined`/`null`. However, `ContentFile.content` is typed as `string` (not optional), so it should never be `undefined` or `null`. The early return for empty string bypasses `marked.parse`, which would return `\"\"` for `\"\"` input anyway. This is harmless but the guard is slightly misleading -- it appears to handle null safety for a non-nullable field.\n\n---\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| # | Plugin | Priority | Issue |\n|---|--------|----------|-------|\n| HIGH-1 | markdown-ext | HIGH | Admonition regex fragile with edge-case formatting |\n| HIGH-2 | markdown-ext | HIGH | Footnotes silently ignore non-numeric IDs |\n| HIGH-3 | markdown-ext | HIGH | Orphaned footnote references produce broken anchor links |\n| HIGH-4 | rss-feed | HIGH | No XML escaping for titles, links, or categories |\n| HIGH-5 | rss-feed | HIGH | Trailing blank line in item output from category template |\n| HIGH-6 | sitemap | HIGH | Includes `search-index.json` in sitemap (non-page resource) |\n| MEDIUM-1 | markdown-ext | MEDIUM | Brittle `as string` cast on `marked.parse()` return |\n| MEDIUM-2 | asset-pipeline | MEDIUM | Only handles `./` relative paths, misses `../` and bare relative |\n| MEDIUM-3 | asset-pipeline | MEDIUM | Only matches `src`/`href` attributes, misses `srcset`/`poster`/etc. |\n| MEDIUM-4 | search-index | MEDIUM | Naive `stripHtml` can mangle text with `<`/`>` in content |\n| MEDIUM-5 | taxonomy | MEDIUM | File titles not HTML-escaped in generated tag pages |\n| MEDIUM-6 | taxonomy | MEDIUM | Root-relative URLs in tag pages vs absolute URLs in RSS feed |\n| MEDIUM-7 | dev-server | MEDIUM | `searchIndexPath` uses empty string instead of null when absent |\n| MEDIUM-8 | markdown-ext | MEDIUM | Unnecessary null guard for non-nullable `content` field |\n\n### What was done well\n\n- All 60 tests pass cleanly and the test coverage is solid for the happy path.\n- Plugin architecture is clean: each plugin is a pure factory function returning a `Plugin` interface with clearly separated hook phases (`beforeBuild`, `transformContent`, `afterBuild`).\n- Cross-plugin data sharing via `ctx.data` is well-designed and consistently used (e.g., `asset-manifest`, `taxonomy-tags`, `dev-server-config`).\n- Dependencies are correctly declared in each plugin's `dependencies` array, matching actual data flow (e.g., `rss-feed` depends on `markdown-ext` and `taxonomy`; `dev-server` depends on `asset-pipeline` and `search-index`).\n- Immutability is respected: `transformContent` hooks return new objects via spread (`{ ...file, content }`) rather than mutating the input.\n- The `sitemap` plugin correctly self-excludes to avoid infinite recursion.\n- Test helpers (`makeCtx`, `makeFile`) are well-factored and consistent across all 8 test files.\n\n### Key Recommendations\n\n1. **Highest impact fix:** Add an `escapeXml()` utility and apply it in `rss-feed.ts` for all interpolated values outside CDATA. This is the most likely bug to manifest with real-world content (titles containing `&`).\n\n2. **Second highest impact:** Add an `escapeHtml()` utility and apply it in `taxonomy.ts` tag page generation. Same class of bug as the XML escaping issue.\n\n3. **Third:** Expand footnote ID support in `markdown-ext.ts` from `\\d+` to `[\\w-]+` to match common Markdown footnote conventions, or add explicit documentation noting the numeric-only limitation.\n\n4. **Fourth:** Improve `stripHtml()` in `search-index.ts` to also decode HTML entities after stripping tags, using a simple entity map for `&amp;`, `&lt;`, `&gt;`, `&quot;`, `&#39;`."}],"totalDurationMs":112197,"totalTokens":34557,"totalToolUseCount":21,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":415,"cache_read_input_tokens":29678,"output_tokens":4463,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":415},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[]}}}
